HEADWORD: Choleric
<hw>Chol"er*ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>cholericus</ets>, Gr. <?/: cf. F.
<ets>chol⟦eacute⟧rique</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Abounding with, or
producing choler, or bile.</def> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Easily irritated; irascible; inclined to
anger.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Angry; indicating anger; excited by anger.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Choleric</xex> speech.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Sir W.
Raleigh.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Choleric temperament</b></col>, <cd>the bilious
temperament.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Cholericly</ent>⟦br⟧
